{"/service/ndnp/oru/batch_oru_longspur_ver01/data/sn88086023/0020219462A/1908020401/0920.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE ETC.1IT.\nMarketing Becomes a Pleasure\nJWhen you can do it in a store where\ncleanliness, convenience and comlort, are\ndistinct features. You'll find these things\nfully embraced in our store.\nJ Added to this the superlative quality of\nour groceries and provisions, our generous\nmethods and our prompt and efficient de\nlivery system and you have the chief ele\nments of our trade-winning combination.\nStandard Grocery Co.\n\"The BestlGroceries'\nMOD IS COMING\nFIKST CIIIUSTIAX CHl'KCH\nSECURES KEY. J. P. MYEKS.\n:Uegular Preaching Services Conduct\ned by the New Pastor Will lie Re-\nsumrd Xext Sunday Morning Uev.\nMyers lias Bern Engaged In the\nBanking Business at North Pow\nder, But Will Permanently Resume\nIlls Calling In This City Comes\nHighly Commended.\n3UXY CONVERSIONS.\nunto salvation, \"a saviour of life unto\nlife or of death unto death.\" The\ndarkest Ufa In eternity will be the\nlife that has had the most light here\nbut has rejected It. There Is a call\nof the holy spirit that many are\nhearing Just now In these days. God\ncalls by tho death angel. This portion\nof the sermon wns especially touch\ning and convincing to many present.\nThe reasons why men refuse the\ncall were sot forth according to the\nscripture In relation to the text. Men\n\"hate knowledge,\" they \"will not\nchoose the fonr of the 'Lord.\" They\nare more afraid of men than they are\nof God. The command Is \"fear God\nand keep His commandments.\"\nTonight the sermon will be on \"The\nUnpardonable Sin, what It Is and who\nare committing It.\" Mr. Hauden\nschleld made the statement In con\nnection with his announcement that\nthere were men In Pendleton who are\ncommitting\" this sin.\nTomorrow morning there will be\ncottage prayer meetings In the fol\nlowing homes: B. E. Coon, Kaley\nstreet; J. Stockman, 623 Garfield;\nMrs, D. Turner, East Court and Lee;\nMrs. Ward, 510 Mill; Mrs. Bamsdell,\nSlS Thompson; Mrs. A. D. Hall. 315\nWest High; Mrs. KImbrell, Chestnut\nand Railroad avenue; Mrs. Lewellen,\n409 West Webb.\nThe First Christian church of this\ncity which has been without a regu\nlar pastor for the past two months,\nhas secured Rev. Jesse P. Myers,\nformerly of Portland, but recently of\n.North Powder, as pastor and he will\narrive in time to have charge of the\ncervices next Sunday morning and\nwill remain permanently thereafter.\n.Rev. Myers is a highly educated\nand eloquent man and comes highly\ncommended to the congregation of\nthe Christian church. He formerly\npreached in the state of Missouri but\nfor some time past has been engaged\nin the banking business at North\nPowder. His father was a banker\nand the son was naturally attracted\nto that industry and for a short time\nhas been out of the active ministry,\nbutVill resume that calling and ex\npects to remain permanently in this\ncity.\nHe is about 40 years of age and\nhas a family.\nThe congregation is delighted to\nsecure his services and Is anticipat\ning with much pleasure the resump\ntion of regular preaching services be\nginning with next Sunday. The re\nvival now in progress has added a\nlarge number of new members and\nthe church starts the new year wltn\nbetter prospects than ever before\nMooting at Christian Church Con\ntinue Wltta Good HuKs Prof.\nIJnnt Leave for Home.\nLast night at the Christian church\nwns a repetition of the great Sunday\nservice when 20 took their stand for\nChrist Last night 14 took this stand.\nmaking 71 to date.\nWilson proved himself an adept in\nleading the music, though Prof. Llnnt\nand his solo work was missed, the\nsinging was as good.\nFor a number of years Evangelist\nWilson held his meetings and did his\nown leading In the music. His text\nfor last night was. \"Naaman the\nLeper.\" which was most ably handl-\nde. Though Xaaman was a great\nman he had to condescend to God's\ncommand before he was healed of\nhis leprosy, to dip ceven times In the\nJordan. Wilson showed how that\nsix times would net do, but that it\ntook the full command of seven. So\nwe to have our sls washed away\nmust obey God's command in full.\nWilson' sermon tonight will be,\n\"Shall we know 6tr friends in\nHeaven?\" After the 1 sermon there\nwill be a number of baptisms. Nine\nwere baptised last night.\nKennedy's Laxative Cough Syrup\nacts aently but promptly on the bow\nels. It stops the cough by soothing\nthe threat and lung Irritation. Sold\nby Tall man Co.\nCOLDS\nThe very hour a cold starts Is the\ntime to check tt JDon't wait It may\nbecome deep-seated and the cure will\nbe harder then. Every hour lost at\nthe start may add days to your sur\nferlng. Taks\nF S\nCold Capsules\nUsed In time they save all that\nmight follow sickness, awry, ex\npenses. They never fall.\nTallman &Co.\nLeading Druggists.\nNEVE ANSWER THE CALL.\nInterest rnabated at the Union\nEvangelistic Services The Un\npardonable Sin\" Tonight.\nAfter the strenuous work of Sun\nday In the union meetings It was ex\npected by many that the meeting last\nnight would be of little consequence\nWhile the audience was not a large\nas on other evenings, the Interest was\nnot abated. At the close of the ser\nmon nine came forward in response\nto the invitation of the evangelist A\nconspicuous feature of the meetings\nIs the number of men In attendance,\nLast night by actual count there were\nmore men than women present.\nThe sermon on 'The Last Call\" was\nan exposition of the call of God to\nmen from the time sin entered the\nworld to the present. Men may at\ntimes be unconscious of the call, but\nthat does not change the fact of the\ncall.- The call comes through the\nBible; which is like a guide book\nfor the soul of man. If a man Is\nlost with the book In his pocket,\nthere is no excuse for him. God calls\nthrough the preaching of the word.\nThe gospel is the power of God\nA FACT PROVEN.\nShould Coavlaee T.rtm the Moat fkep.\ntlral of Its Truth.\nIf there Is the slightest doubt In the\ntitnds of any that Dandruff germs jo not\nexist, their belief la compelled by the\nfact that a rabbit innoculated w'th the\nserrna became bald in six week;' time.\nIt must be apparent to any person\ntherefore that the only prevention of\nbaldness is the destruction of the; serm\nwhich act Is successfully accomplished\n!n one hundred per cent, of :ases by\nthe application of Newbro's Iierpiciae\nDandruff is caused by the same grm\nwhich causes baldness and can be pre\nvented with the same remedy Newbro's\nHerplcide.\nAccept no substitute. \"Destroy the\nsause you remove tne effect.\"\nSold by leading drugrists. Hend Wc. It\nstamps for sample to The Htrplclde Co.\nOetroit. Mich.\nTwo sixes 60 cents and 11.00.\nA. O. Koeppen A Bros.\nI Do You Gel Your Portion of Iho Cream 7\nAre you absolutely certain that your milk is free from\ndirt or infection and that it is Handled in a clean, sanitary\nmanner? The only way to procure good rich, clean milk\nnot that with the cream poured off is to get milk in\nbottles.\nThat is the KindSefl\nPendleton Creamery Co.\nPhone Main 155\n8th Semi-Annual\nPayment of Interest.\nThe regular semi-annual Installment of interest on deposits\nIn the Savings Department of this bank Will be due and credited\non February first. Same will be ready for payment on or after\nthat date. Interest not withdrawn will be added to principal.\nCommercial National Bank\nUNlTEPflSTATES DEPOSITORY, j\nHAAGA DENIES THEFT.\nSays Pnrt of Goods Were Given Him\nas Presents and Part Were Left in\nHis Care.\nAfter five days of trial the state\ncompleted Its testimony In the Hnaga\ncase at 11 o'clock this forenoon and\nsoon afterwards the defense began.\nIts inning with Haaga himself as his\nown first witness. At the opening of\ncourt this morning Albert Janes, a\nmember of the recent grand Jury,\nwas called to the stand and after him\nseveral of the witnesses who had pre\nviously testified were recalled.\nHaaga Denies All.\nWhen placed upon the stand Haa\nga, who Is charged with stealing many\nthings from the George Miller store\nof Echo, denied that he had gotten\npossession of any of the articles by\ntheft. Some of the things he said he\nhad purchased, others had been given\nto him as Christmas presents while\nsome of the articles had been left In\nhis care.\nGOOD PROSPECTS\nFOR IffiEl MY\nMANY IWHMKKS AHE LIST\nING STOCK AXD OTHER GOODS\nMuiuigcr Wittier Announces Change\nof Salon Hour From Afternoon to\nMorning to Accommodate .the\nIurgo Number of Patrous-Alrcady\nOver 40 Head of Cattle and Horses\nHave limit- KcgistweU for Sale\nSome line Stock U He Offered.\nIt is announced by. Sam Blttner,\nmanager of the market day pro\ngram, that at the next sales day; Sat\nurday, February 8, the sale will com\nmence at 10:30 Instead of in the\nafternoon as was the case at the for\nmer sale. By commencing at the ear\nlier hour plenty of time will be given\nfor the sale and the change should\nbe beneficial to both buyers and sell\ners. The sale will again be held at\nthe fair pavilion and arrangements\nare being made to have three auc\ntioneers. That the coming sales day will be\na big event is indicated by the im\nmense amount of stock, etc.', already\nlisted for sale. o far about 40 head\nof horses and cattle have been regis\ntered and more are expected. Among\nthe horses to be sold are some fine\nanimals. Aside from the stock much\nharness, several wagons and other\nfarming equipment will be sold.\nThat the coming sale and the sub\nsequent ones will prove a success is\npredicted by Mr. Blttner and he is\npersonally doing everything possible\nto bring such about.\nBees Laxative Cough Syrup for\ncoughs, colds, croup and whooping\ncough grows In favor dally. Moth\ners should keep It on hand for chil\ndren. It is prompt relief for croup.\nIt Is gently laxative, driving the\npoison and phlegm from the system.\nIt gives immediate relief. Guaran\nteed. Sold by A. C. Koeppen\nBros.\nFruit Crop In Fine Shape.\n\"Weather conditions are most fa\nvorable for a bumper fruit crop,\" J\nsaid Deputy State Horticultural In- i\nspector Mohl this morning when ask\ned relative to the Influence of the\npresent cold weather on the fruit\nsituation, says the Lewlston Teller.\n\"The entire season has been favor\nable for fruit and reports from all\nsections Indicate the trees are in\nsplendid condition to withstand cold\nweather. The buds have not ad\nvanced and fruit would be perfectly\nsafe with a -temperature of 10 de\ngrees below zero.\n\"The fall grain will not suffer by\nthe cold weather,\" continued Mr.\nMohl. \"On the highlands the grain\nIs covered with a blanket of snow,\nand the absence of rain for the past\nseveral weeks prevents an upheaval\nof the ground by the cold weather.\"\nHere From Wane County.\nH. A. Walker, a former resident of\nWeston, but now residing at Wasco,\ncounty, Is In the city today on\nhis return home from Weston, where\nhe has been on a visit. Crop condi\ntions In Wasco are excellent so far\nand farmers are delighted with the\nprospect. Much of the former wheat\ndistrict in Wasco county has been\nplanted to fruit and this Is becoming\na leading industry In many parts or\nthat section.\nComing to Pendleton to Live.\nMr. and Mrs. B. F. Champ, parents\nof Mrs. O. E. Harper of this city, have\nJust sold out their business In San\nJacincto, Cal., and will come to Pen\ndleton to reside permanently. They\nexpect to arrive In about 10 days.\nThey have been In business In San\nJacincto for a number of years, but\nhave been attracted to this city by\nthe excellent business outlook and\nclimatic conditions.\nMany l'aKSengers Transfer.\nAbout 25 passengers transferred\nfrom No. 5. the main line O. ft. N.\ntrain, to the Spokane branch this\nmorning. The main line train did not\narrive until after 10 a. m. and It was\ntoo late to make the transfer to the\nSpokane train at Umatilla. Most of\nthe passengers leaving the main line\nhere were homeseekers bound for\neastern Washington and northern\nIdaho points.\nHl.slops to Move to Portland.\nWithin a short time Mr. and Mrs.\nW. T. Hlslop will move to Portland,\nwhere Mr. Hlslop will henceforth\nhave his headquarters. He is now\nthe northwest representative of the\nJohn S. Ainsfleld company of Cleve\nland, O. They expect to leave Pen\ndleton in about 10 days hut while they\nwill have their home In Portland will\nbe here frequently, as. Mr. Hlslop\nhas considerable property In the city.\nWoodmen Will Give Dance.\nPendleton camp, No. 41, Woodmen\nof the World will give a dance at\nEagles' hall next Monday evening,\nFebruary 10, for Woodmen and their\nwives and members of both Pendleton\nand Daphne Circles of the Women of\nWoodcraft. The dance will be free\nto all those Invited and a pleasant\ntime is expected,\nConductor Smith to Los Angel.\nConductor J. B. Smith of the Pert-\ndleton-Huntington passenger run on\nthe O. R. N. lett tnis morning iur\nAnirelps. where he was called by\nthe condition of Mrs. Smith, who has\nbeen there for her health for the past\ntwo months. She Is not Improving\nas rapidly as was hoped and it Is pos\nsible that a change will oe maae 10\nsome other locality, perhaps to New\nMexico.\nTo stop that pain In the back, that\nstiffness of the Joints and muscles,\ntake Plneules. They are guaranteed.\nDon't suffer from rheumatism, back\nache, kidney trouble, when you get\nSO days' treatment for $1. A s'ngle\ndose at bed time proves their merit\nGet them today. Sold by A. C. Koep\npen Bros.\nBought Mutton Hand.\nNate Raines has purchased a band\nof 1400 mutton sheep from Rugg\nBros. The sheep will be shipped out\nover the N. P. to Freye-Bruhn of Seattle.\nThe real philosopher Is one who\ncan think cheerful thoughts wnne\nnursing a case of the grip.\nind Chdd-\niiixiryjoenua\nCleanses the Sy.stem Effect\nually, Dispels Colas and Head\naches due to Constipation;\nActs naturally, acts truly as\na Laxative.\nTl it II .T\nuesi forlUen.Women ai\nren-Vbungand Ola\nlojjj